<ns0:entry xmlns:ns0="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:ns1="http://schemas.google.com/g/2005" xmlns:ns2="http://schemas.google.com/projecthosting/issues/2009" ns1:etag="W/&quot;D04HR347eCl7ImA9WhNTFE0.&quot;">
		<ns0:id>http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/3083</ns0:id><ns0:author>
			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">In src/trusted/desc/linux/nacl_desc_sysv_shm.c, NaClDescSysvShmMap() contains a call to mmap() which is intended to overwrite an existing mapping, but because MAP_FIXED isn't passed to mmap(), it fails to do so.  Instead, the new mapping goes into trusted address space and is never freed.

After many calls to NaClDescSysvShmMap(), untrusted address space can eventually run out and NaCl trusted code will exit with the fatal error &amp;quot;NaClDescSysvShmMap: Couldn't map the tail page&amp;quot;.

This is much more likely to happen on x86-32 due to the limited address space.

This error has been observed on Chrome OS when creating images in PPAPI in a loop.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2012-10-16T16:45:36.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2012-10-12T05:06:42.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:status>Fixed</ns2:status><ns2:owner>
			<ns2:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns2:uri><ns2:username>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns2:username></ns2:owner><ns2:state>closed</ns2:state><ns0:title>Linux: NaClDescSysvShmMap() leaks trusted address space</ns0:title><ns2:label>Type-Defect</ns2:label><ns2:label>Pri-1</ns2:label><ns2:label>Component-TCB</ns2:label><ns2:label>OS-Linux</ns2:label><ns2:label>Arch-All</ns2:label><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/3083/comments/full" rel="replies" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=3083" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/3083" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><ns2:stars>2</ns2:stars><ns2:closedDate>2012-10-16T16:45:36.000Z</ns2:closedDate><ns2:id>3083</ns2:id></ns0:entry>